'''Alê Abreu''' (born March 6, 1971) is a Brazilian [[film director]] and [[screenwriter]]. ''Sírius'', his first short film, debuted at the 1993 [[Anima Mundi (event)|Anima Mundi]] as the only Brazilian animation that year.<ref name=animamundi>{{cite web | url=http://blog.animamundi.com.br/ale-abreu-e-seus-20-anos-de-anima-mundi/ | title=Alê Abreu e seus 20 anos de Anima Mundi | author=Cataldi, Bruna | date=July 29, 2012 | publisher=Anima Mundi's blog | accessdate=May 1, 2014 | language=Portuguese | archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140501031714/http://blog.animamundi.com.br/ale-abreu-e-seus-20-anos-de-anima-mundi/ | archivedate=2014-05-01 | dead-url=no | df= }}</ref> It won the Best Film Award at the Festival de Cine para Niños y Jovenes and was also screened at the [[Mostra Internacional de Cinema São Paulo]] and at the section Animation for Children of the [[Hiroshima International Animation Festival]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.estadao.com.br/arquivo/arteelazer/2001/not20010312p1693.htm | title=Alê Abreu prepara novo filme de animação | date=March 12, 2001 | work=[[O Estado de S. Paulo]] | publisher=Grupo Estado | accessdate=May 1, 2014  | language=Portuguese}}</ref> His second short film, ''Espantalho'' (lit. "Scarecrow"), released in 1998, won the 3rd Best Brazilian Animation at the Anima Mundi,<ref name=animamundi/> the Best Art Direction Award at the [[Brazilian Film Festival of Miami]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.brazilianfilmfestival.com/miami/2010/miami_past_1999.html | title=3º Brazilian Film Festival of Miami | publisher=Brazilian Film Festival of Miami | accessdate=May 1, 2014  | language=Portuguese}}</ref> and was nominated for Best Animated Feature at the [[1st Grande Prêmio Cinema Brasil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acervo.folha.com.br/fsp/2000/02/12/21 |title=É uma festa! |date=February 12, 2000 |work=Folha de S.Paulo |publisher=Grupo Folha |accessdate=May 1, 2014 |language=Portuguese |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228023002/http://acervo.folha.com.br/fsp/2000/02/12/21 |archivedate=February 28, 2014 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> His first feature film, ''[[Garoto Cósmico]]'', debuted at the 2007 Anima Mundi.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://hqmaniacs.uol.com.br/Festival_Anima_Mundi_comeca_semana_que_vem_12015.html | title=Festival Anima Mundi começa semana que vem |  date=June 22, 2007 | work=HQManiacs | publisher=[[Universo Online]] | accessdate=May 1, 2014 | language=Portuguese}}</ref> In 2013, at the [[Ottawa International Animation Festival]], he released his second film, ''[[Boy and the World]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.animationfestival.ca/pdfs/Features_FINAL.pdf | title=Monty Python Returns! | publisher=[[Ottawa International Animation Festival]] | accessdate=May 1, 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502003928/http://www.animationfestival.ca/pdfs/Features_FINAL.pdf | archive-date=May 2, 2014 | dead-url=yes | df=mdy-all }}</ref> This film became an international success, was nominated at the [[88th Academy Awards]] for [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature|Best Animated Feature]],<ref>http://oscar.go.com/nominees/animated-feature-film/boy-and-the-world</ref> and won several prizes, including the Best Feature Film at the [[Annecy International Animated Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/boy-world-wins-top-prize-711893 | title='The Boy and the World' Wins Top Prize at Annecy Awards | date=June 14, 2014 | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | accessdate=June 16, 2014}}</ref> and the Best Animated Feature-Independent at the [[Annie Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = ASIFA-Hollywood {{!}} Pixar's 'Inside Out' and 'Boy and the World' Win Top Prizes at Annie Awards|url = http://www.asifa-hollywood.org/pixars-inside-out-and-boy-and-the-world-win-top-prizes-at-annie-awards/|website = www.asifa-hollywood.org|access-date = 2016-02-08}}</ref>

